summary: Good Omens
body:
Good Omens

Finally, finally, finally, got to watch Good Omens. I’ve been eagerly awaiting to see it since I first heard it was in the works well over a year ago and it MORE than meets my expectations. (I would have watched it sooner, but I don’t have my own Prime account and I of course had to reread the book for the nth time before watching.)

First of all, I don’t think I’ve ever seen a better book to movie adaptation ever in my life. Though I have to admit, when I first heard about the show being made I had thought, ‘ugh, one of my all time favorite books, and it’s going to be ruined.’ I was, of course, wrong, and I have never been more happy to be wrong about anything.

And then, when I heard that Micheal Sheen was being considered for the role of Aziraphale I thought, ‘really? that’s not quite what I expected.’ Again I was absolutely wrong. Michael Sheen is adorable and an absolute treasure. He played the role spectacularly. As a matter of fact, all of the acting has been spectacular. (I knew Tennant would be wonderful as Crowley and there, at least, I was right).

Also– God and Pollution being women? Fucking brilliant.

Good Omens is one of the best books I’ve ever read. And I’m so happy that so many others are getting to experience this. I do have to advise that you read the book thought, if you haven’t already.

Edit: Basically, I fucking love Good Omens. I love the diversity in casting, and I had forgotten to mention my appreciation for all the wonderful little Easter eggs and add ins, like the addition of Gabriel, Gaimans Cameos, and Pratchetts hat.

Terry Pratchett was an absolutely amazing author, and it’s sad that he didn’t get to be here to be a part of the show, and the inclusion of his hat in the bookshop was sweet.

Ps. If you haven’t read any of Pratchetts work, check out the Discword series. You won’t regret it.

summary: I was reading a delightful article on good omens and I’d really recommend the entirety of it BUT that being said this is the...
body:
I was reading a delightful article on good omens and I’d really recommend the entirety of it BUT that being said this is the funniest and most on-the-nose thing any article has pointed out, ever:

“In the novel, this relationship is fairly sexless and fraternal. The show maintains that on paper. There are no “I love you” declarations in the script or other little touches of suggested intimacy. 

The problem is, well, David Tennant plays Crowley, and there is just nothing sexless or fraternal about David Tennant, ever. Especially not when he is sauntering around in black skinny jeans.”

summary: Appreciation post
body:
Appreciation post

I feel like we don’t talk enough about the moment they drop off Anathema and Crowley says “Get in angel” so so softly.

Right in that moment he sounds somewhat tired and you can feel that he can’t wait to take his angel home in his car, listening to queen quietly thinking about how the world will end in a few days. How he doesn’t want that how he only wants to be with Azeriaphel, doing dumb shit through out time. Keep falling in love and saving each other from whatever harm. How he can’t live without him. How much he loves him.

And it really shows how much of an amazing actor David is because that single moment, how he uses his voice, makes me think all these things and it makes me understand Crowley’s situation and….that’s beautiful.
